New Hope for India
Cambridge, USA — India's latest election may be the most significant positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Indian National Congress, which has almost ruled India since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be glad they made this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and leader of the Indian National Congress, has been ruling from behind the scenes since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh was merely a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Indian National Congress pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led to India's annual economic growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised during his campaign to bring rapid growth in employment and income across all of India, similar to what he achieved as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, expanding economic activity and attracting business investment from both within and outside India.
A significant feature of the latest election is that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) gained an absolute majority in the National Parliament, which can be considered a historic achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties in order to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will assist Modi in his economic plan.
The new finance minister, Arun Jaitley, has extensive political experience and has served as a minister in previous BJP governments.
Jaitley is also known as a strategic thinker sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as governor of the Reserve Bank of India (central bank). Rajan is an outstanding economist who, during his tenure as governor of the Reserve Bank of India, showed a desire to reduce India's double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to reform some inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities provided by these institutions, because primary and secondary education in India is very poor.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy at the primary school level.
Teachers themselves are poorly educated and lack motivation, with many teachers never even showing up at the schools where they are supposed to teach.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
Recent expansions in private airlines and airports indicate that private enterprises can also make contributions in this area.
Fiscal integration.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings that could otherwise be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
State-owned manufacturing and other industrial enterprises in India operate inefficiently and often result in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Electricity and energy subsidies lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, due to the implementation of a new fingerprint-based cash transfer system, cash transfer payments in India are relatively efficient.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is that large quantities of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives are misaligned.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and zoning.
As long as you have been to Mumbai or other major Indian cities, you will see that zoning restrictions lead to poor urban land use and constrain development.
Unclear property rights, especially agricultural property rights, prevent industrialization in rural areas.
Relaxing foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign companies cannot be majority shareholders in banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex national and state sales tax system distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a federal tax system has been ongoing for a long time, and now it should move into the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption scandals have undermined economic confidence and hindered officials' decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by small-scale corruption, with bribery having become a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should strictly punish high-level corruption and limit small-scale corruption through a new cash transfer system.
Driven by expectations of stronger growth and increased profits, India's stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their campaign promises.
